              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">You wanna play a Scum and Villany deck?</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=334"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=334"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=369">Michael "faramir" Dalton</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 369 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">A discussion of the pros and cons of different starts to Scum and Villany decks.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">	If you are anything like me, when this card came out in Jabba's Palace you were very excited about it.  You probably made a deck based around it as soon as you could.  However if you were a competitive player you soon realized that the DS just didn't have the characters to stand up to the light side.  Whether it was Throne Room/Monks that made you fight for your activation, or some other LS Mains deck, it was just too difficult to compete.  Well things have changed, we have gotten very powerful DS characters in ECC and EJP and guess what, time to break out those Scum and Villanies again!  Now the question though, how to play it?	What's the best start for a Scum and Villany deck?  I'll examine the pros and cons of various starts in this article.<br>
<br>
#1: Court of the Vile Gangster<br>
<br>
This objective was made for Scum and Villany.  You start w/ 3 sites, Great Pit of Carkoon, Audience Chamber and Dungeon.  1 of the big advantages of this start is that you can use your Twi'lek Advisor to deploy Scum and Villany, potentially followed up by a 1st turn SE Jabba and some deploy -2 aliens to back him up.	Other than that I don't like this start too much, you don't get any more sites out unless you flip (cause you are not starting Jabba's Palace), and you are vulnerable to someone converting you Audience Chamber before you go.  Against 'You Can Either Profit By This..' decks you can use Chall Bekan to pull a CC Technician and reconvert the Audience Chamber, but against an Obi's Hut/Careful Planning start they could very well convert your AC before you go and turn it into a force advantage (6-4) for them.  Another disadvantage is that you provide a site for your opponent to deploy where they can get around None Shall Pass.  Some things to note however, the objective has a ton of bonuses, and if you plan to take advantage of these bonuses (get independent ships from reserve, bounty hunters improved stats, visage like damage, and huge turns in force if you feed your creatures) it is a very good start for a Scum and Villany deck.  However, if you aren't, I'd suggest some other opening.<br>
<br>
#2: Carbon Chamber Testing<br>
<br>
This one gets overlooked a little bit I believe.  It's got a great advantage in that you really don't have to worry about your opponent converting your locations (which most of these decks do have to worry about).  You start w/ 2 locations, Security Tower and Carbonite Chamber and can pull the Audience Chamber from reserve (as well as docking bays, but those aren't all the useful).  You are spread out on 2 planets, but this can be an advantage as your opponent will have to devote their mains to 1 or the other (assuming you can limit Nabrun Leids).  However as with all of these decks, controlling the Audience Chamber is most important.  This opening benefits over many others because you don't have to waste your starting interrupt on Combat Readiness, and you still get 4 force 1st turn atleast for a 1st turn Jabba.<br>
<br>
#3: Tatooine and Combat Readiness for Jabba's Palace<br>
<br>
This is a very nice start, it gets a 4-2 force advantage and you can pull out the Audience Chamber and a number of 1/0 locations.  It also sets up nicely for Tatooine Occupation and the use of Battle Order.	Presence of the Force can be used to turn more locations into battlegrounds for bigger Occupation loss.  None Shall Pass can be effectively used to keep the opponent out of Jabba's Palace although providing them the system to deploy to allows them to shuttle down to your locations.  There's 1 major problem w/ this start however, a LS player playing on Tatooine and using Careful Planning.  Most LS players who see a DS player starting Tatooine w/ Combat Readiness will assume the DS player is going for Jabba's Palace and will want to deny them this start.  So the DS player has a decision to make, pull Jabba's Palace w/ Combat Readiness and risk it getting converted, or go for the Audience Chamber to guarantee it will be on the table.  This causes lots of problems, especially if the DS player was relying on the Jabba's Palace game text to get out sites for force generation.  If Tatooine starts aren't popular for the LS in your area there's not much to worry about, go with this, but be careful.<br>
<br>
#4: a Tatooine site and Combat Readiness for Jabba's Palace<br>
<br>
This is rather similiar to #3 above.  It's a more ground focused strategy however, you don't need to worry about protecting the system and can instead go for a drain for 2 location.  Jundland Wastes, Lar's Farm, or the Cantina would probably be the most likely choices (although Mos Eisley is an option).  This start suffers from the same problem as #3, a LS player playing on Tatooine and using Careful Planning could very well go for Tat:JP to deny you access to that site.	Again, you could pull out the Audience Chamber instead.  Another negative of this start is that you provide a location for your opponent to deploy to again, negating some benefits of None Shall Pass.  The bonus is that you can set yourself up for major drains on Tatooine, especially if Expand the Empire is used w/ a +1 drain site.<br>
<br>
#5: Tatooine:JP start<br>
<br>
This is really an ideal start if you know that your starting location won't get converted before you go, but that's just not a chance a competitive tournament player can take.  A LS player playing Careful Planning on Tatooine would see your start and immediatly go to convert your location.  1 possible solution however is to have variety in your potential starts, if you see your opponent go Throne Room start then go for No Bargain and deny them a 1st turn rebel to stop your activation.  However if they start 'Profit..' or a Tatooine location and Careful Planning you can go for Combat Readiness and deploy the Audience Chamber.  A useful strategy to combine this with would be to use the Audience Chamber to get Chall Bekan, and Chall Bekan to get a Cloud City Engineer to bring your Tat:JP site to the top.  This opening is rather flexible, I haven't tried it out yet, but I definitely will, it seems strong.<br>
<br>
#6: ISB Operations<br>
<br>
This is an entirely different way to go.  It's got advantages in that the ISB objective is very strong, you get drain bonuses for yourself, and drain minuses for your opponent, but as a Scum and Villany start, it's not too useful as you get no locations.  You'd definitely need to play Jabba's Palace and the Audience Chamber in multiple to pull this off, but the benefits of using the objective may make this well worth it.  Of course in order to play this effectively you need Outer Rim Scouts by the bunch as they are the best alien ISB agents (along w/ their leader Chall Bekan :).<br>
<br>
	I'm sure there are some starts that I've left out here, but I've tried to touch on the most popular ones.  The DS has gotten some really great characters with EJP and ECC, and stand a much better chance of standing toe-to-toe w/ LS Mains, but my suggestion would be to try and avoid it as much as possible.  Playing w/ No Bargain, Bad Feeling Have I and None Shall Pass will help you protect your Audience Chamber much more easily.  This will allow you to pick and choose your battles (knowing that any force you lose you can retrieve later when you find some battles that you want to fight).  I'm pretty excited about Scum and Villany decks starting to see some serious tournament action, I know I've been playing around with one for a while now and a lot of top players have as well.	So give it a try, these decks are a ton of fun to play! - Mike.<br>
 </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=334"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=334"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=334" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
